# Agent Instructions

This project is a .NET transactional integration job built on the Intropy
framework. It reads files from a local Dapr file binding, publishes each one
onto an in-memory Dapr pub/sub topic, and processes them through a VETER send
pipeline that writes the transformed result to a second local file binding.

## Project overview

- Framework: .NET 10
- App type: Console job (no web endpoints)
- Runner: `Intropy.Framework.Hosting.TransactionalIntegration.Job.TransactionalIntegrationRunner`
- App id: `{{ .appId }}`
- Pub/sub component: `pubsub` (in-memory)
- Topic: `orders`
- Source binding: `inbound-storage` (Dapr local storage, rootPath `./local/storage/inbound`)
- Destination binding: `outbound-storage` (Dapr local storage, rootPath `./local/storage/outbound`)
{{- if not .empty }}
- Idempotency Service: reached via Dapr service invocation, app id `idempotency-service`
  (locally an `HTTPEndpoint` component pointing at `http://127.0.0.1:8080`)
- Business Incident Service: reached via Dapr service invocation, app id
  `business-incident-service` (locally an `HTTPEndpoint` at `http://127.0.0.1:8081`)
{{- end }}

## Important files

- `Taskfile.yml` - local-dev tasks; `task run` is the canonical way to run the job.
- `Dockerfile` - multi-stage image build on the .NET chiseled runtime
  (`docker build -t {{ .appId }} .`); the image contains only the app — the
  Dapr sidecar and components come from the deployment environment.
- `src/Program.cs` - DI wiring and entrypoint that runs the `TransactionalIntegrationRunner`.
- `src/Configuration/Constants.cs` - component names, keyed-adapter keys, context metadata keys.
- `src/Receive/` - source listing and the receive pipeline steps (`Receiver`, `Enqueuer`, `Completer`).
- `src/Send/` - the VETER send pipeline steps.
- `test/` - xUnit tests for the send pipeline steps (`task test`).
- `local/dapr-components/` - the job's local Dapr components (pub/sub, storage bindings,
  HTTPEndpoints for the platform services).
- `local/platform-services/` - Docker Compose + Dapr components for the local
  Idempotency Service and Business Incident Service (included by `docker-compose.yml`).
- `local/sample-data/sample-order.json` - sample input seeded into the inbound folder.

## Build and run

`task run` is the canonical run path. It seeds the inbound folder with the
sample order, starts the local stack (grafana/otel-lgtm plus the Idempotency
Service and Business Incident Service with their backing stores), and runs the
job once under Dapr with OTLP export configured; the job exits when done.

```bash
task run
```

Other tasks: `task build` (dotnet build), `task test` (dotnet test), `task clean`
(stop the Dapr app and remove `./local/storage`), `task services:down` (stop the
local stack). See `Taskfile.yml` for ports and flags.

## Development notes

- Source and destination `IFileAdapter` instances are registered as keyed singletons
  (`Constants.SourceFileAdapterKey`, `Constants.DestinationFileAdapterKey`). Inject them
  via `[FromKeyedServices(...)]` or resolve via `GetRequiredKeyedService<IFileAdapter>(...)`.
{{- if .empty }}
- The pipelines are scaffolded without idempotency or business-incident wiring.
  When you implement the step bodies, also add `.WithIdempotency(client, idExtractor,
  dateExtractor)` and `.WithBusinessIncidents(client, messageIdExtractor, subjectExtractor)`
  to the send pipeline builder in `Send/ServiceCollectionExtensions.cs` (and
  `.WithBusinessIncidents(...)` on the receive pipeline), register the clients in
  `Program.cs` with `services.AddIdempotencyServiceClient()` and
  `services.AddBusinessIncidentServiceClient()`, and pick a stable business identifier
  and business timestamp for the idempotency extractors.
{{- else }}
- The send pipeline checks idempotency before transforming: the id is the order's
  `OrderId` and the timestamp its `OrderDate`, so a redelivered unchanged order
  cancels as a traceable no-op instead of writing twice. Keep the id/date extractors
  pointing at *business* fields — a per-delivery value (fresh GUID, wall-clock time)
  makes the check pass everything.
- Business failures (validation, receive errors) are routed to the Business Incident
  Service; the send pipeline keys incidents on the order id, the receive pipeline on
  the source file name.
- Impure values originate in `Deserializer` and travel via `Context.Metadata`
  (`order_id`, `processed_at`); later steps stay pure and unit-testable.
{{- end }}

## Framework guidance

How-to knowledge for the Intropy framework (pipelines, blocks, endpoints, Dapr components, testing) lives in the Intropy skills collection under `.agents/skills/`. If it is not installed, run `intropy skills collection add --name intropy --ref harbor.intropy.io/skills/index:latest`.
